A .NET Temporal workflow uses the following cleanup pattern during cancellation:

```csharp
[WorkflowRun]
public async Task RunAsync()
{
    try
    {
        await Workflow.ExecuteActivityAsync(
            (MyActivities a) => a.MyNormalActivity(),
            new() { ScheduleToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5) });
    }
    catch (Exception e) when (TemporalException.IsCanceledException(e))
    {
        using var detachedCancelSource = new CancellationTokenSource();
        await Workflow.ExecuteActivityAsync(
            (MyActivities a) => a.MyCancellationCleanupActivity(),
            new()
            {
                ScheduleToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5),
                CancellationToken = detachedCancelSource.Token
            });
        throw;
    }
}
```

A teammate refactors the cleanup activity call to reuse `Workflow.CancellationToken` instead of creating a new `CancellationTokenSource`, arguing it avoids unnecessary object allocation. What is the production impact of this change, and which Temporal determinism constraint makes it dangerous?
